1.0 (or 1.1?):

Get the regular version, not the inst version.

The tar file extracts itself into the current directory rather than
creating a new directory.

./ns-install
	/uns/lib/netscape

That was always enough for me.  Craig Kaplan recommends putting in /uns/bin
a shell script something like the following; he says it's good to set
MOZILLA_HOME, which overrides lots of things you would otherwise have to set.

#!/bin/sh
MOZILLA_HOME=/uns/netscape-45; export MOZILLA_HOME
cd /uns/netscape-45
./netscape "$@"

===========================================================================

Follow these steps to install Communicator: 

  1.Download the gzip compressed Communicator tar archive. 

  2.Uncompress and extract the tar file: gzip -dc filename | tar -xvf - 

  3.When the file is uncompressed, a Bourne shell script called
    ns-install will be created. Type ./ns-install 

  4.When prompted, either press Return/Enter to accept the default,
    or enter the path to the installation directory of your choice. You
    will be notified if you do not have permission to install in the
    directory specified or if the directory does not exist. 

    To run Communicator after installation type: cd
    the_directory_you_just_installed_to ./netscape 

If you do not wish to use ns-install, or want to perform a custom
installation, please consult the README.install file. Once you have
restarted your computer, go to the folder where you installed your new
software. Double-click on the Communicator or Navigator application
to launch your new browser. 

===========================================================================



